<div id="review_2190151422" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2190151422" />
    <a title="Natalie (CuriousReader)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6548813-natalie-curiousreader"><img alt="Natalie (CuriousReader)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1476533404p2/6548813.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2190151422?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Natalie (CuriousReader)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Natalie (CuriousReader)" href="/user/show/6548813-natalie-curiousreader">Natalie (CuriousReader)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780241261644" href="/book/show/29607495-wind-sand-and-stars">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6548813-natalie-curiousreader?shelf=translated">translated</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2190151422" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15361603931322918136">Originally published on my blog: <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://curiousreaderr.wordpress.com/2020/04/19/guided-by-stars-wind-sand-and-stars-antoine-de-saint-exupery/'>https://curiousreaderr.wordpress.com/...</a><br/><br/>Once in a while you read a book where you immediately connect with its auteur. So it was for me with Wind, Sand, and Stars by Antoine de Saint-Exupery. I had of course read his most well-known work, The Little Prince, before. In fact out of all of my reading history, it is my most revisited book. For some reason I hadn’t given much thought about its creator since it was a childhood favourite, like many others I had fallen i</span>
  <span id="freeText15361603931322918136" style="display:none">Originally published on my blog: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://curiousreaderr.wordpress.com/2020/04/19/guided-by-stars-wind-sand-and-stars-antoine-de-saint-exupery/">https://curiousreaderr.wordpress.com/...</a><br /><br />Once in a while you read a book where you immediately connect with its auteur. So it was for me with Wind, Sand, and Stars by Antoine de Saint-Exupery. I had of course read his most well-known work, The Little Prince, before. In fact out of all of my reading history, it is my most revisited book. For some reason I hadn’t given much thought about its creator since it was a childhood favourite, like many others I had fallen in love with the vibrant imagery and philosophical stances of the children’s novella. But in Wind, Sand, and Stars we are invited into the man’s own recollections and contemplations — about life as an aviator and the act of flying, wars and class differences, travel and nature, humanity and common purposes of life. It ends up being a thoughtful examination of these things with beautiful insight and way of communicating these musings to the reader.<br /><br />One of my favourite themes on which the Saint-Exupéry writes about is his experiences as a pilot and of flying. I did find the topic itself interesting – being someone who finds travel exciting and anxiety-inducing in equal measure – and the fact of course that he was doing this flying in an entirely different time – around the 1920s and 1930s, before the planes were prepared to the modern level of safety standards. But what truly made it soar was not so much the topic itself but the way it brought the writer alive in so many words, you can tell how passionate he is about his vocation and of sharing his unique experience with a larger audience – to convey the wonders of facing the sky with almost no barriers, to be guided by stars, to know of the dangers lurking behind opaque clouds. Even if you weren’t interested in flying I think you would find his enthusiasm and splendour praise-worthy.<br /><br />Of course much of the book has larger discussions of general human experiences. Some of his observations are based on his travels and meeting with people in the middle-east, slaves or soldiers, traders or new friends; other insights comes from meeting the harshness of nature being stranded in the desert or hearing the story of a comrade lost in the Andes. In the book’s final chapter he talks about humanity’s shared experiences beyond all of our differences:<br /><br /><blockquote>There is no purpose in discussing ideologies. They can all be demonstrated and yet be set against each other, and such discussions bring us only despair for the salvation of mankind, while all around us men themselves display the same needs. We want to be set free.</blockquote><br /><br />While also concluding the essential of a life with purpose, being crucially connected with death:<br /><br /><blockquote>Only when we become aware of the part we play, even the most unobtrusive part, will we be happy. Only then will we live in peace and die in peace, for what gives meaning to life gives meaning to death.</blockquote><br /><br />A reader with less of an appetite for philosophical meanderings might find certain conclusions too grand or wide-reaching, but as Saint-Exupéry grounds even his most grandiose reasonings on his personal experience it never came off as lofty to me. Rather I felt rewarded in being able to connect with a person rendering the world nearly 100 years before me, and still finding most of it as true as what I can see around me with my own eyes. I could make a review only filled with all of the sentences I have underlined, of which there are many – but I will leave you with this last one, especially apt I think in these turbulent times we find ourselves in:<br /><br /><blockquote>We grow rich as we plant through the early years, but then come the years when time undoes our work and cuts down our trees. One by one our comrades deprive us of their shade, and within our mourning we always feel now the secret grief of growing old. [..] there is only one true form of wealth, that of human contact.</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="15361603931322918136" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


